== Not a Blog
My favorite undergraduate classes at Berkeley were [https://sites.google.com/berkeley.edu/ee123-sp20/home EE 123], [https://inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~cs152/sp19/ CS 152], and [https://inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~ee126/sp19/ EECS 126]. I personally don't much like (unnecessarily) banging my head against the wall to solve homework\/lab\/project\/research problems, so my single best piece of advice for succeeding in a university environment would be to never underestimate the power of asking someone else for their thoughts on a problem. Office hours are an especially valuable vehicle for learning simply because they are a manifestation of this principle. \n

I have not recovered emotionally from the closures of [https://sf.eater.com/2019/8/23/20830236/jayakarta-indonesian-restaurant-berkeley-closing Jayakarta Restaurant] and [https://www.chaatcafes.com/ Chaat Cafe] on University Ave. [https://www.yelp.com/biz/lucky-house-thai-berkeley Lucky House Thai] is sadly the last remaining member of my preferred hole-in-the-wall trifecta. Berkeley now is very different from Berkeley five years ago and will be very different from Berkeley five years from now. Unfortunately, it's quite difficult to visit the Ethiopian and Eritrean restaurants in Oakland regularly, but I certainly try my best. 

== More About Me
I've lived in a few places across the United States, including a number of locations within Alabama, Georgia, and California. I also once spent a summer working and studying in Toronto, Canada, and that was a rather enjoyable experience. My native language is Kannada, although I picked up English once I started going to school and kind of forgot most of my Kannada. I hope to re-learn it at some point in the near future. In the meantime, I've had quite a bit of fun learning Italian (in high school) and Hindi (in college). Italians and Indians are very similar in that they really appreciate foreigners learning their languages! I confess that cuisine was my primary motivator in selecting these specific languages to learn. Perhaps I should consider learning Amharic or Tigrinya? \n

My amateur radio call sign is KN6IFM. I have a black belt in [http://www.aikidosv.com/ Kokikai Aikido], which I have practiced for 9 years (including many interruptions since starting college). I also like reading fantasy/science-fiction novels; two of my favorite authors are [https://www.willwight.com/ Will Wight] and [https://jeff-wheeler.com/ Jeff Wheeler]. Since 2009, as an extended exercise in personal character development, I have supported [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tottenham_Hotspur_F.C. Tottenham Hotspur Football Club], devotedly watching my team go through lows like being hammered 5-1 by a 10-man, already-relegated Newcastle United on the last day of the 2015-16 season and highs like reaching its first-ever UEFA Champions League Final, during the 2018-19 season.

